{"title":"DoughNet: A Visual Predictive Model for Topological Manipulation of Deformable Objects","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"Robots need to predict how elastoplastic objects will deform and undergo topological changes (merging, splitting, self-merging) under different end-effector geometries and actions from partial RGB-D observations, which prior methods largely ignore or handle post hoc.","method":"DoughNet introduces a Transformer-based denoising autoencoder that embeds a partial point cloud into a fixed-size set of latent codes, which a decoder turns into per-component 3D occupancy masks plus per-component genus labels. A topology-aware dynamics model then autoregressively predicts the next set of latents conditioned on the embedded end-effector geometry (sampled surface points over two time steps). Training uses permutation-invariant reconstruction with focal loss and a Huber loss directly on latent sets over two steps to mitigate exposure bias, enabling joint long-horizon prediction of geometry and topology without post-hoc topology checks."},{"problem":"Obtaining ground-truth dynamic topology (when and how components merge/split) for elastoplastic manipulation is ill-defined from particle data and infeasible to annotate on real observations.","method":"The paper proposes physically plausible topology-checking operations within an MPM-based simulator: counterfactual velocity perturbations are applied to candidate regions to test whether they remain connected (merge) or separate (split), updating a scene-topology graph over time. Using particle labels, component surface meshes are extracted via signed-distance grids and Dual Contouring, and realistic single-view, noisy, partial depth observations are rendered. This synthetic data generator provides consistent geometry, component labels, and topology supervision to train DoughNet."},{"problem":"Planning topological manipulation from a single partial view requires selecting not only actions but also tool geometry and pose to achieve a target geometry/topology.","method":"DoughNet is integrated with a CEM planner that rolls out action sequences in latent space and scores them by cosine similarity to the goal latents, naturally capturing both geometry and topology. The sampled action space includes in-plane translations/rotations and discrete end-effector geometry and opening width; distributions are iteratively refit to top-performing samples. This enables accurate selection of tool, pose, and opening width to reproduce robot- and human-made goals in simulation and on real hardware from single RGB-D observations."}]}
